—faced two ongoing challenges: how to develop objective, internationally recognized scientific authority without effacing native identity, and how to serve China when China was still searching for a stable national form. Shen argues that Chinese geologists overcame these obstacles by experimenting with different ways to associate the subjects of their scientific study, the land and its features, with the object of their political and cultural loyalties. This, in turn, led them to link national survival with the establishment of scientific authority in Chinese society. The first major history of modern Chinese geology, Unearthing the Nation introduces the key figures in the rise of the field, as well as several key organizations, such as the Geological Society of China, and explains how they helped bring Chinese geology onto the world stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGeologistszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGeologyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalism and science. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ageological, geology, science, scientific, scientist, national, nationalism, republican, china, chinese, eastern, east, identity, political, politics, social, culture, cultural, 1900s, 20th century, contemporary, modern, diverse, diversity, technology, modernization, interdisciplinary, native, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, domestic, community.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022609040540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226090542423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226090542/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles